item.title: katas Raj Temple
item.description:
SMBukhari posted a photo:

The temple of Katas Raj, located in the salt range 18 miles south of Chakwal, is found in Maha Bharat written in 300 BC. The etymology of this place as narrated in the old edition of Tarikh-i-Jhelum (History of Jhelum) is that according to Brahaman belief, Shiv Devta wept so profusely on the death of his beloved wife Satti that two holy ponds – one at Pushkar of Ajmair and other at Katak Shell – came into being with his tears. In Sanskrit, Katak Shell – means chain of tears which later on was pronounced as ‘Katas’

item.description:

I took a few shots of this black headed gull at Sutton Bingham Reservoir, near Yeovil in Somerset, but it was only when i got home and viewed the pictures on my computer that i realised it only had one leg!!
Poor bird!
It seemed quite happy flying about though.....i suppose one wing would have been more of a handicap! ;-)

item.title: Rosemary Beetle
item.description:
pallab seth posted a photo:

A Rosemary Beetle (Chrysolina americana) on a dried Lavender branch!

The beetle devours the leaves of rosemary, lavender, thyme, sage and some other related plants.
It is an attractive 5mm long metallic green beetle with purple stripes on its wing cases and thorax.
The beetle is a native of southern Europe that has become an established pest in Britain since the 1990s.

item.title: Blue Green
item.description:
Roy Prasad posted a photo:

Best seen on black - press L or click image above.

Since blue and green are adjacent colors in the spectrum, it is always a challenge to make these colors work together. Certain shades of blues and greens work very well, like dark greens of the leaves of a tree against a light blue sky. At other times, they conflict. The same applies to green and yellow, which are also adjacent colors. But when such colors complement each other, the result is pleasing.

Leica S2 + Leica APO Macro Summarit-S 120mm f/2.5
S2202805
